Subject: [PATCH] IMAGING-220: replace while by if in the JPEG decoder extend
 method


diff --git a/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/imaging/formats/jpeg/decoder/JpegDecoder.java b/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/imaging/formats/jpeg/decoder/JpegDecoder.java
index 3561fcbc..2b21da2c 100644
--- a/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/imaging/formats/jpeg/decoder/JpegDecoder.java
+++ b/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/imaging/formats/jpeg/decoder/JpegDecoder.java
@@ -400,7 +400,7 @@ public class JpegDecoder extends BinaryFileParser implements JpegUtils.Visitor {
     private int extend(int v, final int t) {
         // "EXTEND", section F.2.2.1, figure F.12, page 105 of T.81
         int vt = (1 << (t - 1));
-        while (v < vt) {
+        if (v < vt) {
             vt = (-1 << t) + 1;
             v += vt;
         }

The code statements that lead to the bug are:
```java
while (v < vt) {
    vt = (-1 << t) + 1;
    v += vt;
}
```
Reason:
The use of a `while` loop allows for multiple iterations as long as the condition `v < vt` is true. This can lead to incorrect value adjustments and potentially an infinite loop if `v` never reaches or exceeds `vt`, which is not the intended behavior.

The code statements that fix the bug are:
```java
if (v < vt) {
    vt = (-1 << t) + 1;
    v += vt;
}
```
Reason:
Replacing the `while` loop with an `if` statement ensures that the adjustment to `v` occurs only once when the condition `v < vt` is true. This prevents the possibility of multiple iterations and eliminates the risk of an infinite loop, thus fixing the bug in the JPEG decoding process.

